{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"7bdb646c-0bcf-47e6-bc8b-dee0c7385232","content":"Here's how to collect a trace from a .NET 8 app in a Windows container on Kubernetes:\n\n### 1. Exec into the container\n```powershell\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n### 2. Install `dotnet-trace`\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n```\n\n### 3. Find the process ID\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n### 4. Collect the trace\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --duration 00:00:30 --profile cpu-sampling\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can analyze with **Visual Studio** or **PerfView**.\n\n### 5. Copy the trace out\n```powershell\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:<path-to-trace-file> ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n### Alternative: Use `dotnet-counters` first\nIf you want a quick look before committing to a full trace:\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-counters\ndotnet-counters monitor -p <PID>\n```\n\n> **Tip:** If the global tools path isn't in `$PATH` inside the container, use the full path (typically `$env:USERPROFILE\\.dotnet\\tools\\dotnet-trace`). If the container image doesn't include the .NET SDK, you can [sidecar-copy the tools](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/diagnostics/) or enable the diagnostic port via `DOTNET_DiagnosticPorts` and connect from the host.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"8c321108-314e-409a-99ef-67657d6cfcbe","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes. This is a troubleshooting/diagnostic question, not a code change request. I'll provide concise guidance.","outputTokens":457,"requestId":"7641:19B167:D294CD:F68B7A:69FE8C60"},"id":"3d1f7971-fd6c-457b-9bc1-bb4056c008b0","timestamp":"2026-05-09T01:22:51.236Z","parentId":"65de05c8-284d-458e-a1c8-90889b7c79d7"}
